    <para id="id14268920">By Dimensional Balance the correctness of the Equation(1.26) is established.</para>
    <para id="id17176722">Eq.(1.26) tells us that only spheres of orbital radius r<sub>n</sub> = n<sup>2</sup>.h<sup>2</sup>.ε<sub>0</sub>/(m<sub>e</sub>.q<sup>2</sup>.π) are permitted.</para>
    <para id="id12626686"/>
    <para id="id19836478">The radius of the first and innermost spherical orbit = 0.529Å;</para>
    <para id="id7694114">The radius of the second spherical orbit = 2.116 Å because n=2;</para>
    <para id="id15085831">The radius of the third spherical orbit = 4.761 Å because n=3;</para>
    <para id="id11980895">Thus we see that only a given number of spherical orbits having Bohr radii are permitted around the nucleus of an Atom. Also in these permissible orbits the standing wave boundary conditions are fulfilled as shown in Fig.(1.14)</para>
